  "why": "ASDF uses a differential-testing design (so semantic-preservation relative to the original seed is not required), and it enforces input naturalness across its mutation stage: transformed texts are produced via linguistically-motivated methods (e.g., homophone, tense changes, WordHoard examples) and are explicitly filtered for realism by requiring that each transformed text be transcribable (i.e., determinable) by at least one ASR before being kept. The framework also performs only a single transformation iteration (first iteration → transform failed texts → second iteration), avoiding repeated relative-to-last-mutant mutations that would allow cumulative drift. These points show the tool enforces naturalness where applicable and, because the oracle is differential, semantic-consistency constraints relative to the original seed are not applicable.",
